The paper deals with approximation algorithms for constraint satisfaction problems (CSPs), which are a fundamental topic in theoretical computer science. The paper also mentions specific CSPs such as Max-Cut, Max-Dicut, and k-SAT, which are commonly studied in the computational complexity community. Therefore, cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) are likely categories. The paper also discusses the denseness requirement on input instances, which relates to graph theory and combinatorics, making cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) a possible category. Additionally, the paper mentions the running time of the algorithm, which is a common topic in computational geometry (cs.CG) and graph theory (cs.GT).
